{"title_page": "A. P. Younger", "text_new": "{{short description|American screenwriter}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = A.P. Younger\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date  = September 25, 1890\n| birth_place = [[Sacramento, California]], US\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1931|11|29|1890|9|25}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], US\n| yearsactive = 1919\u20131931\n}}\n\n'''A.P. Younger'''; born Andrew Percy Younger (September 25, 1890 &ndash; November 29, 1931) was an American [[screenwriter]]. He was born in [[Sacramento, California]], and he wrote for 60 films between 1919 and 1931. Younger shot himself to death by accident on November 29, 1931, at his private residence at 145 Beachwood Drive in [[Windsor Square, Los Angeles|Windsor Square]], [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |title=Screen Writer Shot To Death. A. P. Younger, Dialogue Man, Slain Testing Pistol. Accident Caused by Effort to Quiet Barking Dog. Stepson Rushes to Aid After Fatal Shell Explosion |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/380281660/?terms=%22A.%2BP.%2BYounger%22 |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=November 30, 1931|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\"stlouispostdispatchobit\">{{cite news |title=A. P. Younger, Film Writer, Kills Self By Accident |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/138849310/?terms=%22A.%2BP.%2BYounger%22 |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=November 30, 1931|page=6|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Fair and Warmer (1919 film)|Fair and Warmer]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Are All Men Alike?]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The Man Tamer]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[Rich Girl, Poor Girl]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[The Galloping Kid]]'' (1922) (scenario)\n* ''[[The Lone Hand (1922 film)|The Lone Hand]]'' (1922) \n* ''[[Drifting (1923 film)|Drifting]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Why Men Leave Home]]'' (1924)\n* ''[[Adventure (1925 film)|Adventure]]'' (1925) \n* ''[[Souls for Sables]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Brown of Harvard (1926 film)|Brown of Harvard]]'' (1926) (scenario)\n* ''[[Slide, Kelly, Slide]]'' (1927) (scenario)\n* ''[[Sally (1929 film)|Sally]]'' (1929) (uncredited scenario)\n* ''[[The Girl Said No (1930 film)|The Girl Said No]]'' (1930) (story)\n* ''[[Sunny Skies (film)|Sunny Skies (1930 film)]]'' (1930) (story)\n* ''[[The Single Sin]]'' (1931)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0950224|name=A.P. Younger}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Younger, A.P.}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Firearm accident victims in the United States]]\n{{US-screen-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American screenwriter}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = A.P. Younger\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date  = September 25, 1890\n| birth_place = [[Sacramento, California]], USA\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1931|11|29|1890|9|25}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], USA\n| yearsactive = 1919-1931\n}}\n\n'''A.P. Younger'''; born Andrew Percy Younger (September 25, 1890 &ndash; November 29, 1931) was an American [[screenwriter]]. He was born in [[Sacramento, California]], and he wrote for 60 films between 1919 and 1931. Younger shot himself to death by accident on November 29, 1931 at his private residence at 145 Beachwood Drive in [[Windsor Square, Los Angeles|Windsor Square]], [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite news |title=Screen Writer Shot To Death. A. P. Younger, Dialogue Man, Slain Testing Pistol. Accident Caused by Effort to Quiet Barking Dog. Stepson Rushes to Aid Aft